    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i checked the spark plugs and they look okay. vacuum leaks seem like a possibility though. how do i actually test for those? like is there a specific way to find where the air is coming in?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For vacuum leak detection, you will first need to listen for hissing noise at the intake manifold, looking for any signs of air escaping, which may indicate a leak. You can also place a vacuum gauge at the manifold and check for drop in vacuum pressure with various joints and hoses tightness inspected one by one. Using a smoke machine or spray varnish can make this easier by depositing soot or varnish at the leak point, which is more visually observable. Another method is to remove the intake manifold and visually inspect joints, hoses, and gaskets for damage or loss of tightness that would allow air to enter. This may require disconnecting several components, and depending on your experience, might be a good time to also look for torn O-rings or damage to the carbon seals. Be sure to properly reassemble and secure all parts once the leaks are found and repaired.",
      "source": "target",
