      "role": "user",
      "content": "i dont have a smoke machine or a vacuum gauge handy. if i just use some soapy water or something like that on the hoses and fittings while the engine is idling, will that work to find the leak? should i be looking for bubbles or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, soapy water can be a useful substitute when a smoke machine or vacuum gauge isn't available. You can apply water mixed lightly with dish soap to the gaskets, rubber seals, and around hoses while the engine idles. Look for any bubbling or foaming appearance, which indicates air being pulled in through a leak. This should be done during idle or at a slow speed to prevent the engine from picking too much speed where the leak might not be immediately apparent. Be cautious but thorough – rotate the vehicles while this technique is in progress to inspect all the accessible parts of the intake system. Remember to clean any soapy water residue as soon as it's applied and before reattaching the parts to avoid any affecting future operations.",
